John Edward: Linguistic competencies are fundamental for citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent educational centres have a path of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of extraordinary results in exams that are reinforced by individual and collective successes harvested in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students throughout Scotland, these centers, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges (SCIS) are trying to deliver the best level of service to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students to continue their higher education studies, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in centers.
As Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, it comes to his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that, if you want to establish relationships and generate confidence with people from other countries, you cannot depend only on English.
If we take into account the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the classification tables, with the highest approved rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest score.
The data, collected from the 74 centers that were part of the SCIS, showed that 72 per cent of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of German students, 69 per cent of French students and 63 per cent of Spanish students also obtained an A.
This demonstrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages by considering them a fundamental competence that both children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Currently, languages are considered to be at the same level as CTIM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the study plans of independent schools and everywhere.
A survey conducted in 2014 by the UK Employment and Competence Commission revealed that 17 per cent were attributed to the lack of linguistic competences from the reasons that entrepreneurs gave about their difficulties in covering jobs.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable to prepare young people for their future careers.
Possible job opportunities that require languages are increasing, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career you choose, if you have learned a second language, you will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last your lifetime.
The fact of being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will allow that person to automatically advance competition.
According to a poll conducted by YouGov among more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak any foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation, and it was established that the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for children today.
If you know several languages, especially those in developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality jobs.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centers will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach the most important languages for the UK from 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child are, in independent schools you can always choose from several languages taught by teaching staff specialized in this field.
Scotland’s independent educational centres devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and that teams with the skills needed to succeed, whatever it takes them for the future.
At present, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to have a vital importance for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered "competences for international communication."
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We need to do it.
