North Korea says “there is no possibility” to disarm first unilaterally if they don’t have confidence
On Saturday, the North Korean Foreign Minister informed the United Nations that the continuation of the sanctions deepened its mistrust in the United States and that there was no possibility for his country to unilaterally resign to nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho declared to the annual General Assembly of the international agency that North Korea had taken "important goodwill measures" over the past year, such as stoping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling nuclear test facilities and commitment to the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“However, we don’t receive any similar answer from the United States,” he said.
"If we don't have confidence in the United States, we can't have confidence in our national security, and in those circumstances there's no possibility that we will first disarm ourselves unilaterally."
Although Ri repeated North Korea’s well-known complaints for Washington’s resistance to a “stage-by-phase” denuclearization formula that rewards the country as it takes gradual steps, his statement is important, as he has no longer rejected a unilateral denuclearization, such as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump following the first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim committed to work for the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula" and Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea has pursued the official end of the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must resign before its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted appeals to smooth international sanctions against North Korea.
"The United States has insisted on denuclearization first and have increased pressure through sanctions in order to achieve its purpose in a coercive manner, even by making objections to a statement of ending the war," Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can cause us to fall on our knees is a chimera of the people who don’t know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our distrust.”
Ri made no mention of the plans of a second summit between Kim and Trump, announced by the U.S. leader at the United Nations in the early week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings held between South Korea’s leader Kim and Moon Jae in the last five months, adding: “If South Korea had been the interested party in denuclearization instead of the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not be found in a similar stagnation.”
Even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s speech, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to direct North Korea’s missiles to U.S. soil after the “malignant president” Trump on suicidal mission called Kim “man rocket.”
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "destroy entirely" North Korea, praised Kim for his bravery in progress towards disarmament, but said he remained a lot to be done and it was necessary to continue to apply sanctions until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline set for this: "We can take two years, three years, or five months, no matter."
China and Russia claim that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its progress.
