He left Pyongyang in July saying progress had occurred, but, a few hours later, North Korea denounced that his "requirements were the requirements of a mafious."
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile location and a nuclear complex if the United States applied the "corresponding measures".
He said Kim had told him that the "corresponding measures" he was looking for were the security guarantees that Trump had promised in Singapore and steps towards normalizing relationships with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to rest enough
Thanks to a new course taught this year at Harvard University, all college students sleep more in an attempt to fight the growing machist culture of studying drinking caffeine all night.
A teacher discovered that students at the world’s number one university often have no idea of the basic care of oneself.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard School of Medicine, and a Brigham and Women's Hospital specialist designed the course, is believed to be the first of his class in the U.S.
His motivation to start the course emerged after giving a talk about how sleep deprivation affects learning.
“At the end of the course, a girl approached me and asked me why she just heard of this now, in her last year.
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he said.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits contribute to academic and sports performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard School of Medicine and executive director of university health services, noted that the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students barely slept during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In a section, there is an image of a bedroom, where students click on cups of coffee, curtains, sports shoes and books that inform them of the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on sports performance and the importance of establishing a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of infarction, embolia, depression and cancer.
Then, a campus icon with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know you won’t change students’ behavior instantly.
However, we believe they have the right to know it, just like anyone has the right to know the effects on tobacco smoking on the health,” Professor Czeisler added.
He claimed that the culture of pride for "passing the night on sail" still exists and added that modern technology and increased pressure to which students were subjected meant that sleep deprivation was a growing problem.
Sleeping enough time and a good quality sleep should be "the secret weapon" of students to fight stress, fatigue, and anxiety; even to avoid weight gain, as sleep deprivation causes the brain to generate a feeling of hunger, so they want to eat all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemistry and physics, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after attending one of his classes the previous year during his first year at Harvard.
He pointed out that the course had opened her eyes and inspired to expand it to the entire campus.
It hopes that the next step is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler’s recommendation is that students think of putting an alarm to go to bed and another to wake up, and that they are aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” that emit the screens of electrical apparatus and LEDs, which can alter circadian rhythms, so they would end up having trouble sleeping.
