As part of the treatment, the vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells.
The method requires the removal of immune cells from a patient and altering them in the laboratory.
Thus, they can "see" a protein common to many cancers and reinject them.
A vaccine trial is generating promising results in patients with different cancers.
A woman treated with the vaccine, who teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells, saw how her ovarian cancer disappeared for more than 18 months.
The method requires the removal of immune cells from a patient and altering them in the laboratory so that they can "see" a protein common to many cancers, called HER2, and then reinject the cells.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the U.S. National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, commented: “Our results suggest that we have a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 "promotes the growth of different types of cancer", such as breast, ovary, lung or colorectal cancer, Berzofsky explained.
A similar approach to taking immune cells from patients and "teaching them" to attack cancer cells has worked in treating a type of leukemia.
