HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% more of new cases
China has announced an increase of 14% in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
There are more than 820,000 people affected in the country, according to health authorities.
Only in the second quarter of 2018, some 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of these were sexually infected, which is a change in relation to the past.
Traditionally, HIV spread rapidly through some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of HIV-contractors in this way has been decreased in virtually their entirety, Chinese health authorities declared at a conference held in Yunnan province.
Each year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increases around 100,000 people.
Sexually transmitting HIV is a serious problem in the LGBT community in China.
Homosexuality was decriminalised in China in 1997, but the LGTB group suffers a lot of discrimination.
Due to the country’s conservative values, studies have estimated that between 70% and 90% of men who have sex with other men will eventually marry women.
Many of the disease transmissions are not to use adequate protection in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV drugs as part of an attempt to address the problem.
