Syria is ready to return refugees, Foreign Minister says
Syria claims that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and requests help in rebuilding a country devastated by a war that has been for more than seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the country's conditions were getting better.
“The situation on the ground is today more stable and secure thanks to the progress that has been achieved in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilite the areas destroyed by terrorists to attempt to restore normality.
All conditions for the voluntary return to the country of refugees who had to abandon it are already given due to terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and their livelihoods.
The UN estimates that, since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people still living in the country and need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would be grateful to help rebuild the devastated country.
But he also emphasized that he would not accept a conditional aid or aid from countries that promoted the insurgence.
