Red Tide Update: Decrease concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report of the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier county, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
The flowering of the red tide extends approximately along 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County north to Lee County south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles from Hillsborough County coastline, but in fewer locations if compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
Last week, average concentrations in the county of Pinellas and its coast have been reported, low to high concentrations in the Hillsborough County coast, high to high concentrations in the county of Manatee, high to high concentrations in the county of Sarasota and its coast, low to average concentrations in the county of Le Col.
Respiratory irritation problems are still reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Respiratory irritation problems have not been reported in the northwest area of Florida last week.
